# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: big-boys-gone-bananas
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/a-place-at-the-table] Participant Media is the entertainment company behind the film, and it is distributed by Magnolia Pictures.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/a-place-at-the-table] The Participant/Magnolia team is also responsible for the film *Food, Inc.* (2008).
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/a-place-at-the-table] The film was originally titled *Finding North* but the name was later changed to *A Place at the Table*.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/a-place-at-the-table] As of 2012, about 50 million Americans were food insecure.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/a-place-at-the-table] This was approximately 1 in 6 of the overall population, with the proportion of children facing food insecurity even higher at about 1 in 4.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/a-place-at-the-table] One in every two children receive federal food assistance.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/a-place-at-the-table] Other Americans struggling with hunger are also featured, including a cop whose monthly paychecks only leaves him enough money to buy food for two weeks, forcing him to use a food bank.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/a-place-at-the-table] There is also a companion book titled *A Place at the Table: The Crisis of 49 Million Hungry Americans and How to Solve It,* edited by Peter Pringle and published by Public Affairs.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/a-place-at-the-table] The book features contributions from Jeff Bridges, Ken Cook, Marion Nestle, Bill Shore, Joel Berg, Robert Egger, Janet Poppendieck, David Beckmann, Mariana Chilton, Tom Colicchio, Jennifer Harris, Andy Fisher, Kelly Meyer and directors Kristi Jacobson and Lori Silverbush.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/a-place-at-the-table] The film was nominated for Grand Jury Prize at the 2012 Sundance Film Festival.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/a-place-at-the-table] At the 2013 IDA Documentary Awards, the film received the Pare Lorentz Award, which recognizes films for model filmmaking while focusing on the use of the natural environment, and justice for all and the illumination of pressing social problems.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/a-place-at-the-table] As of October 2015, it has a 90% approval ratings from 61 professional reviews aggregated by Rotten Tomatoes.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] There are various ways in which antisemitism is manifested, ranging in the level of severity of Jewish persecution.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] On the more subtle end, it consists of expressions of hatred or discrimination against individual Jews and may or may not be accompanied by violence.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] At the extreme, it consists of pogroms or genocide, which may or may not be state-sponsored.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Although the term *antisemitism* did not come into common usage until the 19th century, it is also applied to previous and later anti-Jewish incidents.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Historically, most of the world's violent antisemitic events have taken place in Europe, where modern antisemitism began to emerge from antisemitism in Christian communities during the Middle Ages.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Since the early 20th century, there has been a sharp rise in antisemitic incidents across the Arab world, largely due to the advent of Arab antisemitic conspiracy theories, which were influenced by European antisemitic conspiracy theories.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Beginning in 1879, the compound word *Antisemitismus* was first used in print in Germany as a "scientific-sounding term" for *Judenhass* (lit.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] 'Jew-hatred'), and it has since been used to refer to anti-Jewish sentiment alone.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] In the 21st century, the idea that there is a variation of antisemitism known as "new antisemitism" has been discussed.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] According to this view, since Israel is a Jewish state, expressions of anti-Zionist positions could harbour antisemitic sentiments, and criticism of Israel can serve as a vehicle for attacks against Jews in general.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] First used in the 1770s by members of the Göttingen school of history, the coining of "Semites" as biblical terminology for race was derived from *Shem* (שֵׁם), the name of one of the three sons of Noah in the Book of Genesis, together with the parallel terms *Hamites* and *Japhetites*.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] The origin of "antisemitic" terminologies is found in the responses of Orientalist Moritz Steinschneider to the views of Orientalist Ernest Renan.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Steinschneider used this phrase to characterise the French philosopher Ernest Renan's false ideas about how 'Semitic races' were inferior to 'Aryan races'".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Pseudoscientific theories concerning race, civilization, and "progress" had become quite widespread in Europe in the second half of the 19th century, especially as Prussian nationalistic historian Heinrich von Treitschke did much to promote this form of racism.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] He coined the phrase "the Jews are our misfortune", which would later be widely used by Nazis.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] According to Falk, Treitschke uses the term "Semitic" almost synonymously with "Jewish", in contrast to Renan's use of it to refer to a whole range of peoples, based generally on linguistic criteria.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Hess, the term was originally used by its authors to "stress the radical difference between their own 'antisemitism' and earlier forms of antagonism toward Jews and Judaism".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] In 1879, German journalist Wilhelm Marr published a pamphlet, *Der Sieg des Judenthums über das Germanenthum.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Vom nicht confessionellen Standpunkt aus betrachtet* (*The Victory of the Jewish Spirit over the Germanic Spirit.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Observed from a non-religious perspective*), in which he used the word *Semitismus* interchangeably with the word *Judentum* to denote both "Jewry" (the Jews as a collective) and "Jewishness" (the quality of being Jewish, or the Jewish spirit).
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] He accused the Jews of a worldwide conspiracy against non-Jews, called for resistance against "this foreign power", and claimed that "there will not be a single office in the land, including the highest, which will not have been usurped by the Jews".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] This followed his 1862 book *Der Judenspiegel* (*A Mirror to the Jews*), in which he argued that "Judaism must cease to exist if humanity is to commence", demanding that Judaism be both dissolved as a "religious-denominational sect" and subject to criticism "as a race, a civil and social entity".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] This use of *Semitismus* was followed by a coining of *Antisemitismus*, which was used to indicate opposition to the Jews as a people and opposition to the Jewish spirit, which Marr interpreted as infiltrating German culture.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] The pamphlet became very popular, and in the same year Marr founded the *Antisemiten-Liga* ('League of Antisemites'), apparently named to follow the *Anti-Kanzler-Liga* ('Anti-Chancellor League').
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] The league was the first German organisation committed specifically to combating the alleged threat to Germany and German culture posed by the Jews and their influence and advocating their forced removal from the country.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] So far as can be ascertained, the word was first widely printed in 1881, when Marr published *Zwanglose Antisemitische Hefte*, and Wilhelm Scherer used the term *Antisemiten* in the January issue of *Neue Freie Presse*.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] The *Jewish Encyclopedia* reports, "In February 1881, a correspondent of the *Allgemeine Zeitung des Judentums* speaks of 'Anti-Semitism' as a designation which recently came into use ('Allg.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] The word *antisemitism* was borrowed into English from German in 1881.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] *Oxford English Dictionary* editor James Murray wrote that it was not included in the first edition because "*Anti-Semite* and its family were then probably very new in English use, and not thought likely to be more than passing nonce-words...
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Would that anti-Semitism had had no more than a fleeting interest!" The related term *philosemitism* was used by 1881.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] From the outset the term *anti-Semitism* bore special racial connotations and meant specifically prejudice against Jews.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] The word *Semitic* was coined for use in linguistics by German Orientalist August Ludwig von Schlözer in 1781 to designate the Semitic group of languages—Aramaic, Arabic, Hebrew and others—allegedly spoken by the descendants of the Biblical figure Shem, son of Noah.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Though the general definition of *antisemitism* is 'hostility or prejudice against Jews', and, according to Olaf Blaschke, the word has become an "umbrella term for negative stereotypes about Jews", a number of authorities have developed more formal definitions.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Elaborating on Fein's definition, Dietz Bering of the University of Cologne writes that, to antisemites, "Jews are not only partially but totally bad by nature, that is, their bad traits are incorrigible.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Because of this bad nature: (1) Jews have to be seen not as individuals but as a collective.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] (2) Jews remain essentially alien in the surrounding societies.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] For Swiss historian Sonja Weinberg, as distinct from economic and religious anti-Judaism, antisemitism in its specifically modern form shows conceptual innovation, a resort to "science" to defend itself, new functional forms, and organisational differences.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] It was anti-liberal, racialist and nationalist.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] It promoted the myth that Jews conspired to 'judaise' the world; it served to consolidate social identity; it channeled dissatisfactions among victims of the capitalist system; and it was used as a conservative cultural code to fight emancipation and liberalism.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] In 2003, Israeli politician Natan Sharansky developed what he called the "three D" test to distinguish antisemitism from criticism of Israel, giving Delegitimization, Demonization, and Double standards as a litmus test for the former.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] British-American historian Bernard Lewis, writing in 2006, defined antisemitism as a special case of prejudice, hatred, or persecution directed against people who are in some way different from the rest.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] According to Lewis, antisemitism is marked by two distinct features: Jews are judged according to a standard different from that applied to others, and they are accused of "cosmic evil".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Thus, "it is perfectly possible to hate and even to persecute Jews without necessarily being anti-Semitic" unless this hatred or persecution displays one of the two features specific to antisemitism.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] There have been a number of efforts by international and governmental bodies to define antisemitism formally.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] In 2005, the European Monitoring Centre on Racism and Xenophobia (EUMC, now the Fundamental Rights Agency), an agency of the European Union, developed a more detailed working definition, which stated: "Antisemitism is a certain perception of Jews, which may be expressed as hatred toward Jews.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] The EUMC working definition was adopted by the European Parliament Working Group on Antisemitism in 2010, by the United States Department of State in 2017, in the Operational Hate Crime Guidance of the UK College of Policing in 2014 and by the UK's Campaign Against Antisemitism.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] In 2016, the working definition was adopted by the International Holocaust Remembrance Alliance.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] IHRA's Working definition of antisemitism is among the most controversial documents related to opposition to antisemitism, and critics argue that it has been used to censor criticism of Israel.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] In response to the perceived lack of clarity in the IHRA definition, two new definitions of antisemitism were published in 2021, the Nexus Document in February 2021 and the Jerusalem Declaration on Antisemitism in March 2021.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] In 1879, Wilhelm Marr founded the Antisemiten-Liga (Anti-Semitic League).
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Identification with antisemitism and as an antisemite was politically advantageous in Europe during the late 19th century.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] For example, Karl Lueger, the popular mayor of fin de siècle Vienna, skillfully exploited antisemitism as a way of channeling public discontent to his political advantage.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] In its 1910 obituary of Lueger, *The New York Times* notes that Lueger was "Chairman of the Christian Social Union of the Parliament and of the Anti-Semitic Union of the Diet of Lower Austria.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Cuza organized the *Alianța Antisemită* and the *Liga Antisemită Universală* in Bucharest.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] In the period before World War II, when animosity towards Jews was far more commonplace, it was not uncommon for a person, an organization, or a political party to self-identify as an antisemite or antisemitic.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] The early Zionist pioneer Leon Pinsker, a professional physician, preferred the clinical-sounding term ***Judeophobia*** (also ***Judaeophobia***) to antisemitism, which he regarded as a misnomer.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] The word *Judeophobia* first appeared in his pamphlet *Auto-Emancipation*, published anonymously in German in September 1882, where it was described as an irrational fear or hatred of Jews.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] According to Pinsker, this irrational fear was an inherited predisposition.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] In the aftermath of the Kristallnacht pogrom in 1938, German propaganda minister Goebbels announced: "The German people is anti-Semitic.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] After 1945 victory of the Allies over Nazi Germany, and particularly after the full extent of the Nazi genocide against the Jews became known, the term *antisemitism* acquired pejorative connotations.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] This marked a full circle shift in usage, from an era just decades earlier when "Jew" was used as a pejorative term.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Yehuda Bauer wrote in 1984: "There are no anti-Semites in the world ...
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Nobody says, 'I am anti-Semitic.' You cannot, after Hitler.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] The term has been described as confusing, for in modern usage *Semitic* designates a language group, not a race.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] In this sense, the term is a misnomer, since there are many speakers of Semitic languages (e.g., Arabs, Ethiopians, and Assyrians) who are not the objects of antisemitic prejudices, while there are many Jews who do not speak Hebrew, a Semitic language.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Though *antisemitism* could be construed as prejudice against people who speak Semitic languages, this is not how the term is commonly used.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] The term may be spelled with or without a hyphen (*antisemitism* or *anti-Semitism*).
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Many scholars and institutions favor the unhyphenated form.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] According to Carroll, who first cites O'Hare and Bauer on "the existence of something called 'Semitism'", "the hyphenated word thus reflects the bipolarity that is at the heart of the problem of antisemitism".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Hess identified the operative referent in the original usage to have been "antisemit[e]".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] The Associated Press and its accompanying *AP Stylebook* adopted the unhyphenated spelling in 2021.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Style guides for the *New York Times* and *Wall Street Journal* later adopted this spelling as well.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] It has also been adopted by many Holocaust museums, such as the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum and Yad Vashem.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] The study of antisemitism has become politically controversial because of differing interpretations of the Holocaust and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] There are two competing views of antisemitism—eternalism and contextualism.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] The eternalist view sees antisemitism as separate from other forms of racism and prejudice and an exceptionalist, transhistorical force teleologically culminating in the Holocaust.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Most Zionists do not believe that antisemitism can be combatted with education or other means.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] The contextual approach treats antisemitism as a type of racism and focuses on the historical context in which hatred of Jews emerges.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Some contextualists restrict the use of "antisemitism" to refer exclusively to the era of modern racism, treating anti-Judaism as a separate phenomenon.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Historian David Engel has challenged the project to define antisemitism, arguing that it essentializes Jewish history as one of persecution and discrimination.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Engel argues that the term "antisemitism" is not useful in historical analysis because it implies that there are links between anti-Jewish prejudices expressed in different contexts, without evidence of such a connection.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Antisemitism manifests itself in a variety of ways.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] René König mentions social antisemitism, economic antisemitism, religious antisemitism, and political antisemitism as examples.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] These difficulties may contribute to the existence of different taxonomies that have been developed to categorize the forms of antisemitism.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] The forms identified are substantially the same; it is primarily the number of forms and their definitions that differ.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Bernard Lazare, writing in the 1890s, identified three forms of antisemitism: Christian antisemitism, economic antisemitism, and ethnologic antisemitism.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] William Brustein names four categories: religious, racial, economic, and political.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Louis Harap, writing in the 1980s, separated "economic antisemitism" and merges "political" and "nationalistic" antisemitism into "ideological antisemitism".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Harap also adds a category of "social antisemitism".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Religious antisemitism, also known as anti-Judaism, is antipathy towards Jews because of their perceived religious beliefs.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] In theory, antisemitism and attacks against individual Jews would stop if Jews stopped practicing Judaism or changed their public faith, especially by conversion to the official or right religion.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] However, in some cases, discrimination continues after conversion, as in the case of *marranos* (Christianized Jews in Spain and Portugal) in the late 15th century and 16th century, who were suspected of secretly practising Judaism or Jewish customs.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Although the origins of antisemitism are rooted in the Judeo-Christian conflict, other forms of antisemitism have developed in modern times.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Drumont founded the Antisemitic League of France.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] The underlying premise of economic antisemitism is that Jews perform harmful economic activities or that economic activities become harmful when they are performed by Jews.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Linking Jews and money underpins the most damaging and lasting antisemitic canards.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Antisemites claim that Jews control the world finances, a theory promoted in the fraudulent *The Protocols of the Elders of Zion* and later repeated by Henry Ford and his *The Dearborn Independent*.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] In the modern era, such myths continue to be spread in books such as *The Secret Relationship Between Blacks and Jews* published by the Nation of Islam and on the internet.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Gerald Krefetz summarizes the myth as "[Jews] control the banks, the money supply, the economy, and businesses—of the community, of the country, of the world".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Krefetz gives, as illustrations, many slurs and proverbs (in several different languages) which suggest that Jews are stingy, or greedy, or miserly, or aggressive bargainers.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] During the nineteenth century, Jews were described as "scurrilous, stupid, and tight-fisted", but after the Jewish Emancipation and the rise of Jews to the middle- or upper-class in Europe were portrayed as "clever, devious, and manipulative financiers out to dominate [world finances]".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Léon Poliakov asserts that economic antisemitism is not a distinct form of antisemitism, but merely a manifestation of theologic antisemitism (because, without the theological causes of economic antisemitism, there would be no economic antisemitism).
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] In opposition to this view, Derek Penslar contends that in the modern era, economic antisemitism is "distinct and nearly constant" but theological antisemitism is "often subdued".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] An academic study by Francesco D'Acunto, Marcel Prokopczuk, and Michael Weber showed that people who live in areas of Germany that contain the most brutal history of antisemitic persecution are more likely to be distrustful of finance in general.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Therefore, they tended to invest less money in the stock market and make poor financial decisions.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Racial antisemitism is prejudice against Jews as a racial/ethnic group, rather than Judaism as a religion.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Racial antisemitism is the idea that the Jews are a distinct and inferior race compared to their host nations.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] In the late 19th century and early 20th century, it gained mainstream acceptance as part of the eugenics movement, which categorized non-Europeans as inferior.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] It more specifically claimed that Northern Europeans, or "Aryans", were superior.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Racial antisemites saw the Jews as part of a Semitic race and emphasized their non-European origins and culture.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] They saw Jews as beyond redemption even if they converted to the majority religion.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Racial antisemitism replaced the hatred of Judaism with the hatred of Jews as a group.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] In the context of the Industrial Revolution, following the Jewish Emancipation, Jews rapidly urbanized and experienced a period of greater social mobility.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] With the decreasing role of religion in public life tempering religious antisemitism, a combination of growing nationalism, the rise of eugenics, and resentment at the socio-economic success of the Jews led to the newer, and more virulent, racist antisemitism.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] In the early 19th century, a number of laws enabling the emancipation of the Jews were enacted in Western European countries.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] The old laws restricting them to ghettos, as well as the many laws that limited their property rights, rights of worship and occupation, were rescinded.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Despite this, traditional discrimination and hostility to Jews on religious grounds persisted and was supplemented by racial antisemitism, encouraged by the work of racial theorists such as Joseph Arthur de Gobineau and particularly his *Essay on the Inequality of the Human Race* of 1853–1855.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Nationalist agendas based on ethnicity, known as ethnonationalism, usually excluded the Jews from the national community as an alien race.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Allied to this were theories of Social Darwinism, which stressed a putative conflict between higher and lower races of human beings.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Such theories, usually posited by northern Europeans, advocated the superiority of white Aryans to Semitic Jews.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] William Brustein defines political antisemitism as hostility toward Jews based on the belief that Jews seek national or world power.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Yisrael Gutman characterizes political antisemitism as tending to "lay responsibility on the Jews for defeats and political economic crises" while seeking to "exploit opposition and resistance to Jewish influence as elements in political party platforms." Derek J.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] According to Viktor Karády, political antisemitism became widespread after the legal emancipation of the Jews and sought to reverse some of the consequences of that emancipation.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Holocaust denial and Jewish conspiracy theories are also considered forms of antisemitism.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Zoological conspiracy theories have been propagated by Arab media and Arabic language websites, alleging a "Zionist plot" behind the use of animals to attack civilians or to conduct espionage.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] In this view, the proponents of the new concept believe that criticisms of Israel and Zionism are often disproportionate in degree and unique in kind, and they attribute this to antisemitism.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Jewish scholar Gustavo Perednik posited in 2004 that anti-Zionism in itself represents a form of discrimination against Jews, in that it singles out Jewish national aspirations as an illegitimate and racist endeavor, and "proposes actions that would result in the death of millions of Jews".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p01] Proponents of this theory assert that the new antisemitism deploys traditional antisemitic motifs, including older motifs such as the blood libel.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Many authors see the roots of modern antisemitism in both pagan antiquity and early Christianity.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The first clear examples of anti-Jewish sentiment can be traced to the 3rd century BCE to Alexandria, the home to the largest Jewish diaspora community in the world at the time and where the Septuagint, a Greek translation of the Hebrew Bible, was produced.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Manetho, an Egyptian priest and historian of that era, wrote scathingly of the Jews.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] His themes are repeated in the works of Chaeremon, Lysimachus, Poseidonius, Apollonius Molon, and in Apion and Tacitus.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Agatharchides of Cnidus ridiculed the practices of the Jews and the "absurdity of their Law", making a mocking reference to how Ptolemy Lagus was able to invade Jerusalem in 320 BCE because its inhabitants were observing the *Shabbat*.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] One of the earliest anti-Jewish edicts, promulgated by Antiochus IV Epiphanes in about 170–167 BCE, sparked a revolt of the Maccabees in Judea.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In view of Manetho's anti-Jewish writings, antisemitism may have originated in Egypt and been spread by "the Greek retelling of Ancient Egyptian prejudices".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The ancient Jewish philosopher Philo of Alexandria describes an attack on Jews in Alexandria in 38 CE in which thousands of Jews died.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The violence in Alexandria may have been caused by the Jews being portrayed as misanthropes.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Tcherikover argues that the reason for hatred of Jews in the Hellenistic period was their separateness in the Greek cities, the *poleis*.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Bohak has argued, however, that early animosity against the Jews cannot be regarded as being anti-Judaic or antisemitic unless it arose from attitudes that were held against the Jews alone, and that many Greeks showed animosity toward any group they regarded as barbarians.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Statements exhibiting prejudice against Jews and their religion can be found in the works of many pagan Greek and Roman writers.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Edward Flannery writes that it was the Jews' refusal to accept Greek religious and social standards that marked them out.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] There are examples of Hellenistic rulers desecrating the Temple and banning Jewish religious practices, including Antiochus IV Epiphanes, who in 167 BCE erected an altar to Zeus in the temple directed the sacrifice of pigs to at the altar.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] He also banned Jewish practices such as circumcision, Shabbat observance, and the study of Torah scrolls, sparking the Maccabean Revolt.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The Jewish diaspora on the Nile island Elephantine, which was founded by mercenaries, experienced the destruction of its temple in 410 BCE.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Relationships between the Jewish people and the occupying Roman Empire were at times antagonistic and resulted in several rebellions, most notably the First Jewish–Roman War and the Bar Kokhba revolt.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] According to Suetonius, the emperor Tiberius took measures against Jews in Rome in 19 CE, expelling and relocating some Jewish‑affiliated groups in response to unrest and alleged religious‑moral offenses.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The 18th-century English historian Edward Gibbon identified a more tolerant period in Roman–Jewish relations beginning in about 160 CE.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] However, with the rise of Christianity as the dominant religion, increasingly restrictive legislation and rhetoric was directed against Jews.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] James Carroll asserted: "Jews accounted for 10% of the total population of the Roman Empire.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In the late 6th century CE, the newly Catholicised Visigothic kingdom in Hispania issued a series of anti-Jewish edicts which forbade Jews from marrying Christians, practicing circumcision, and observing Jewish holy days.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Continuing throughout the 7th century, both Visigothic kings and the Church were active in creating social aggression and towards Jews with "civic and ecclesiastic punishments", ranging between forced conversion, slavery, exile and death.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] From the 9th century, the medieval Islamic world classified Jews and Christians as *dhimmis* and allowed Jews to practice their religion more freely than they could do in medieval Christian Europe.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Under Islamic rule, there was a Golden age of Jewish culture in Spain that lasted until at least the 11th century.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] It ended when several Muslim pogroms against Jews took place on the Iberian Peninsula, including those that occurred in Córdoba in 1011 and in Granada in 1066.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Several decrees ordering the destruction of synagogues were also enacted in Egypt, Syria, Iraq and Yemen from the 11th century.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In addition, Jews were forced to convert to Islam or face death in some parts of Yemen, Morocco and Baghdad several times between the 12th and 18th centuries.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The Almohads, who had taken control of the Almoravids' Maghribi and Andalusian territories by 1147, were far more fundamentalist in outlook compared to their predecessors, and they treated the *dhimmis* harshly.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Faced with the choice of either death or conversion, many Jews and Christians emigrated.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Some, such as the family of Maimonides, fled east to more tolerant Muslim lands, while some others went northward to settle in the growing Christian kingdoms.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In medieval Europe, Jews were persecuted with blood libels, expulsions, forced conversions and massacres.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] These persecutions were often justified on religious grounds and reached a first peak during the Crusades.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In 1096, hundreds or thousands of Jews were killed during the First Crusade.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] This was the first major outbreak of anti-Jewish violence in Christian Europe outside Spain and was cited by Zionists in the 19th century as indicating the need for a state of Israel.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In 1147, there were several massacres of Jews during the Second Crusade.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The Shepherds' Crusades of 1251 and 1320 both involved attacks, as did the Rintfleisch massacres in 1298.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Expulsions followed, such as the 1290 banishment of Jews from England, the expulsion of 100,000 Jews from France in 1394, and the 1421 expulsion of thousands of Jews from Austria.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Many of the expelled Jews fled to Poland.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] As the Black Death epidemics devastated Europe in the mid-14th century, causing the death of a large part of the population, Jews were used as scapegoats.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Rumors spread that they caused the disease by deliberately poisoning wells.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Hundreds of Jewish communities were destroyed in numerous persecutions.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Although Pope Clement VI tried to protect them by issuing two papal bulls in 1348, the first on 6 July and an additional one several months later, 900 Jews were burned alive in Strasbourg, where the plague had not yet affected the city.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Martin Luther, an ecclesiastical reformer whose teachings inspired the Reformation, wrote antagonistically about Jews in his pamphlet *On the Jews and their Lies*, written in 1543.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] He portrays the Jews in extremely harsh terms, excoriates them and provides detailed recommendations for a pogrom against them, calling for their permanent oppression and expulsion.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] During the mid-to-late 17th century the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth was devastated by several conflicts, in which the Commonwealth lost over a third of its population (over 3 million people), and Jewish losses were counted in the hundreds of thousands.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The first of these conflicts was the Khmelnytsky Uprising, when Bohdan Khmelnytsky's supporters massacred tens of thousands of Jews in the eastern and southern areas he controlled (today's Ukraine).
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The precise number of dead may never be known, but the decrease of the Jewish population during that period is estimated at 100,000 to 200,000, which also includes emigration, deaths from diseases, and captivity in the Ottoman Empire, called *jasyr*.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] European immigrants to the United States brought antisemitism to the country as early as the 17th century.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Peter Stuyvesant, the Dutch governor of New Amsterdam, implemented plans to prevent Jews from settling in the city.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] During the Colonial Era, the American government limited the political and economic rights of Jews.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] It was not until the American Revolutionary War that Jews gained legal rights, including the right to vote.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] However, even at their peak, the restrictions on Jews in the United States were never as stringent as they had been in Europe.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In the Zaydi imamate of Yemen, Jews were also singled out for discrimination in the 17th century, which culminated in the general expulsion of all Jews from places in Yemen to the arid coastal plain of Tihamah and which became known as the Mawza Exile.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In 1744, Archduchess of Austria Maria Theresa ordered Jews out of Bohemia but soon reversed her position, on the condition that Jews pay for their readmission every ten years.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] This extortion was known among the Jews as *malke-geld* ("queen's money" in Yiddish).
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In 1752, she introduced the law limiting each Jewish family to one son.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In 1782, Joseph II abolished most of these persecution practices in his *Toleranzpatent*, on the condition that Yiddish and Hebrew were eliminated from public records and that judicial autonomy was annulled.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] According to Arnold Ages, Voltaire's "Lettres philosophiques, Dictionnaire philosophique, and Candide, to name but a few of his better known works, are saturated with comments on Jews and Judaism and the vast majority are negative".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The counter-revolutionary Catholic royalist Louis de Bonald stands out among the earliest figures to explicitly call for the reversal of Jewish emancipation in the wake of the French Revolution.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Bonald's attacks on the Jews are likely to have influenced Napoleon's decision to limit the civil rights of Alsatian Jews.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Bonald furthermore declared that the Jews were an "alien" people, a "state within a state", and should be forced to wear a distinctive mark to more easily identify and discriminate against them.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Under the French Second Empire, the popular counter-revolutionary Catholic journalist Louis Veuillot propagated Bonald's arguments against the Jewish "financial aristocracy" along with vicious attacks against the Talmud and the Jews as a "deicidal people" driven by hatred to "enslave" Christians.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Between 1882 and 1886 alone, French priests published twenty antisemitic books blaming France's ills on the Jews and urging the government to consign them back to the ghettos, expel them, or hang them from the gallows.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Gougenot des Mousseaux's *Le Juif, le judaïsme et la judaïsation des peuples chrétiens* (1869) has been called a "Bible of modern antisemitism" and was translated into German by Nazi ideologue Alfred Rosenberg.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Thousands of Jews were slaughtered by Cossack Haidamaks in the 1768 massacre of Uman, in the Kingdom of Poland.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In 1772, the empress of Russia, Catherine II, forced the Jews into the Pale of Settlement—which was located primarily in present-day Poland, Ukraine, and Belarus—and to stay in their shtetls and forbade them from returning to the towns that they occupied before the partition of Poland.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] From 1804, Jews were banned from their villages and began to stream into the towns.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] A decree by emperor Nicholas I of Russia in 1827 conscripted Jews under 18 years of age into the cantonist schools for a 25-year military service in order to promote baptism.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Policy towards Jews was liberalised somewhat under Czar Alexander II (r.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] However, his assassination in 1881 served as a pretext for further repression, such as the May Laws of 1882.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Konstantin Pobedonostsev, nicknamed the "black czar" and tutor to the czarevitch, later crowned Czar Nicholas II, declared that "One-third of the Jews must die, one-third must emigrate, and one third be converted to Christianity".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Historian Martin Gilbert writes that it was in the 19th century that the position of Jews worsened in Muslim countries.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Benny Morris writes that one symbol of Jewish degradation was the phenomenon of stone-throwing at Jews by Muslim children.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In Jerusalem at least, conditions for some Jews improved.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] At the time of the Dreyfus trial in France, "Muslim comments usually favoured the persecuted Jew against his Christian persecutors".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In 1850, the German composer Richard Wagner—who has been called "the inventor of modern antisemitism"—published *Das Judenthum in der Musik* (roughly "Jewishness in Music") under a pseudonym in the *Neue Zeitschrift für Musik*.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Although originally published anonymously, when the essay was republished 19 years later, in 1869, the concept of the corrupting Jew had become so widely held that Wagner's name was affixed to it.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Antisemitism can also be found in many of the Grimms' Fairy Tales by Jacob and Wilhelm Grimm, published from 1812 to 1857.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] It is mainly characterized by Jews being the villain of a story, such as in "The Good Bargain" ("*Der gute Handel*") and "The Jew Among Thorns" ("*Der Jude im Dorn*").
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The middle 19th century saw continued official harassment of the Jews, especially in Eastern Europe under Czarist influence.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] For example, in 1846, 80 Jews approached the governor in Warsaw to retain the right to wear their traditional dress but were immediately rebuffed by having their hair and beards forcefully cut, at their own expense.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Even such influential figures as Walt Whitman tolerated bigotry toward the Jews in America.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] During his time as editor of the Brooklyn Eagle (1846–1848), the newspaper published historical sketches casting Jews in a bad light.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The Dreyfus Affair was an infamous antisemitic event of the late 19th century and early 20th century.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Alfred Dreyfus, a Jewish artillery captain in the French Army, was accused in 1894 of passing secrets to the Germans.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] As a result of these charges, Dreyfus was convicted and sentenced to life imprisonment on Devil's Island.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The actual spy, Marie Charles Esterhazy, was acquitted.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The event caused great uproar among the French, with the public choosing sides on the issue of whether Dreyfus was actually guilty or not. Émile Zola accused the army of corrupting the French justice system.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] However, general consensus held that Dreyfus was guilty: 80% of the press in France condemned him.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] This attitude among the majority of the French population reveals the underlying antisemitism of the time period.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Adolf Stoecker (1835–1909), the Lutheran court chaplain to Kaiser Wilhelm I, founded in 1878 an antisemitic, anti-liberal political party called the Christian Social Party.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] This party always remained small, and its support dwindled after Stoecker's death, with most of its members eventually joining larger conservative groups such as the German National People's Party.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Some scholars view Karl Marx's essay "On The Jewish Question" as antisemitic, and argue that he often used antisemitic epithets in his published and private writings.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] These scholars argue that Marx equated Judaism with capitalism in his essay, helping to spread that idea.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Some further argue that the essay influenced National Socialist, as well as Soviet and Arab antisemites.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Marx himself had Jewish ancestry, and Albert Lindemann and Hyam Maccoby have suggested that he was embarrassed by it.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Others argue that Marx consistently supported Prussian Jewish communities' struggles to achieve equal political rights.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] These scholars argue that "On the Jewish Question" is a critique of Bruno Bauer's arguments that Jews must convert to Christianity before being emancipated, and is more generally a critique of liberal rights discourses and capitalism.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] David McLellan and Francis Wheen argue that readers should interpret *On the Jewish Question* in the deeper context of Marx's debates with Bruno Bauer, author of *The Jewish Question*, about Jewish emancipation in Germany.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Wheen says that "Those critics, who see this as a foretaste of 'Mein Kampf', overlook one, essential point: in spite of the clumsy phraseology and crude stereotyping, the essay was actually written as a defense of the Jews.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] It was a retort to Bruno Bauer, who had argued that Jews should not be granted full civic rights and freedoms unless they were baptised as Christians".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] According to McLellan, Marx used the word *Judentum* colloquially, as meaning *commerce*, arguing that Germans must be emancipated from the capitalist mode of production not Judaism or Jews in particular.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] McLellan concludes that readers should interpret the essay's second half as "an extended pun at Bauer's expense".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Between 1900 and 1924, approximately 1.75 million Jews migrated to America, the bulk from Eastern Europe escaping the pogroms.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] This increase, combined with the upward social mobility of some Jews, contributed to a resurgence of antisemitism.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In the first half of the 20th century, in the US, Jews were discriminated against in employment, access to residential and resort areas, membership in clubs and organizations, and in tightened quotas on Jewish enrolment and teaching positions in colleges and universities.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The lynching of Leo Frank by a mob of prominent citizens in Marietta, Georgia, in 1915 turned the spotlight on antisemitism in the United States.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The case was also used to build support for the renewal of the Ku Klux Klan which had been inactive since 1870.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] At the beginning of the 20th century, the Beilis Trial in Russia represented modern incidents of blood-libels in Europe.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] During the Russian Civil War, close to 50,000 Jews were killed in pogroms.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Antisemitism in America reached its peak during the interwar period.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The pioneer automobile manufacturer Henry Ford propagated antisemitic ideas in his newspaper *The Dearborn Independent* (published by Ford from 1919 to 1927).
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The radio speeches of Father Coughlin in the late 1930s attacked Franklin D.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Roosevelt's New Deal and promoted the notion of a Jewish financial conspiracy.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Some prominent politicians shared such views: Louis T.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] McFadden, Chairman of the United States House Committee on Banking and Currency, blamed Jews for Roosevelt's decision to abandon the gold standard, and claimed that "in the United States today, the Gentiles have the slips of paper while the Jews have the lawful money".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In Germany, shortly after Adolf Hitler and the Nazi Party came to power in 1933, the government instituted repressive legislation which denied Jews basic civil rights.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] These laws culminated in a state-sponsored pogrom on the night of 9–10 November 1938, known as Kristallnacht ("Night of Broken Glass"), during which at least 91 Jews were killed, thousands arrested, over 7,500 Jewish businesses destroyed, and about 1,400 synagogues burned or damaged.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Antisemitic legislation, agitation, and propaganda were subsequently extended to German-occupied Europe following the onset of war in 1939, frequently adapting or amplifying local antisemitic traditions (e.g., in Vichy France and occupied Poland).
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In 1940, the famous aviator Charles Lindbergh and many prominent Americans led the America First Committee in opposing any involvement in a European war.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Lindbergh alleged that Jews were pushing America to go to war against Germany.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Lindbergh adamantly denied being antisemitic, and yet he refers numerous times in his private writings—his letters and diary—to Jewish control of the media being used to pressure the U.S. to get involved in the European war.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In one diary entry in November 1938, he responded to *Kristallnacht* by writing "I do not understand these riots on the part of the Germans. ...
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] They have undoubtedly had a difficult Jewish problem, but why is it necessary to handle it so unreasonably?", acknowledgement on Lindbergh's part that he agreed with the Nazis that Germany had a "Jewish problem".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] An article by Jonathan Marwil in *Antisemitism, A Historical Encyclopedia of Prejudice and Persecution* claims that "no one who ever knew Lindbergh thought him antisemitic" and that claims of his antisemitism were solely tied to the remarks he made in that one speech.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In the east the Third Reich forced Jews into ghettos in Warsaw, in Kraków, in Lvov, in Lublin and in Radom.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] After the beginning of the war between Nazi Germany and the Soviet Union in 1941, a campaign of mass murder, conducted by the Einsatzgruppen, culminated from 1942 to 1945 in systematic genocide: the Holocaust.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Eleven million Jews were targeted for extermination by the Nazis, and some six million were eventually killed.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] There have continued to be antisemitic incidents since WWII, some of which had been state-sponsored.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In the Soviet Union, antisemitism was even used as an instrument for settling personal conflicts, starting with the conflict between Joseph Stalin and Leon Trotsky and continuing through numerous conspiracy theories spread by official propaganda.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Antisemitism in the USSR reached new heights after 1948 during the campaign against the "rootless cosmopolitan" (euphemism for "Jew") in which numerous Yiddish-language poets, writers, painters, and sculptors were killed or arrested.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] This culminated in the antisemitic conspiracy theory of the 'Doctors' Plot' in 1952.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In the 20th century, Soviet and Russian antisemitism underwent significant transformations, shaped by political, social, and ideological shifts.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] During the early Soviet period, the Bolsheviks initially condemned antisemitism, seeing it as incompatible with Marxist ideology.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] However, under Joseph Stalin's regime, antisemitism reemerged, often cloaked in 'anti-Zionist' rhetoric.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] As early as 1943, Stalin and his propagandists intensified attacks against Jews as "rootless cosmopolitans".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The Party issued confidential directives to fire Jews from positions of power, but state-controlled media did not openly attack Jews until the late 1940s.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The Doctors' plot of 1952, a fabricated conspiracy accusing predominantly Jewish doctors of attempting to assassinate Soviet leaders, exemplified this resurgence.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] This campaign fostered widespread antisemitic sentiments and resulted in the arrest and execution of numerous Jewish professionals.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In that same year, the antisemitic Slánský show trial alleged the existence of an 'international Zionist conspiracy' to destroy Socialism.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The Six-Day War in 1967 led to an intensification in Soviet anti-Zionist propaganda as the Soviets had backed the defeated Arab states.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] This propaganda often blurred the lines with antisemitism, leading to discriminatory policies against Jews and restricting their emigration.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] By the end of the war, "the "corporate Jew", whether "cosmopolitan" or "Zionist", became identified as the enemy.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Their propaganda frequently borrowed directly from the forged Protocols of the Elders of Zion and sometimes relied upon Adolf Hitler's *Mein Kampf* as a source of information about Zionism.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Antizionism helped Moscow "bond both with its Arab allies and the Western hard left of all shades.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Similar antisemitic propaganda in Poland resulted in the flight of Polish Jewish survivors from the country.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] After the war, the Kielce pogrom and the "March 1968 events" in communist Poland represented further incidents of antisemitism in Europe.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The anti-Jewish violence in postwar Poland had a common theme of blood libel rumours.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Antisemitism is still prevalent in contemporary far-right politics across much of the globe, whether as overt claims or covert dog-whistles.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Antisemitism has been a key factor for multiple perpetrators of far-right violence and terrorism in recent years, including the Pittsburgh synagogue shooting, the 2018 United States mail bombing attempts, and the Poway synagogue shooting.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Judith Butler, Masha Gessen, and others have identified a mainstreaming of Zionist antisemitism from the far-right under the Trump administrations in the US, with the Zionist Organization of America honouring Steve Bannon in 2017.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Holocaust denial, the claim that the Nazi genocide of European Jews during the Second World War either never happened or is substantially exaggerated by historical accounts, is a form of antisemitism and conspiracy theory.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Political movements seeking to revive the ideologies of the Nazis and other states that participated in the Holocaust, like neo-Nazism and neofascism, practice Holocaust denial.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Rehabilitation of Nazism can also be accomplished on an individual scale.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] There is significant debate about whether analogies between Israel's treatment of Palestinians and the Nazis' treatment of Jews or comparisons to Anti-Palestinianism are antisemitic.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Those who say they are antisemitic have termed such analogies "Holocaust inversion"—a form of Holocaust trivialisation, in which the Holocaust is compared with other events in a way that downplays its severity.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Deborah Lipstadt describes Holocaust inversion as a type of Holocaust denial.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Physical assaults against Jews in Europe have included beatings, stabbings, and other violence, which increased markedly, sometimes resulting in serious injury and death.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] This rise in antisemitic attacks is associated with both Muslim antisemitism and the rise of far-right political parties as a result of the economic crisis of 2008.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] This rise in the support for far-right ideas in western and eastern Europe has resulted in the increase of antisemitic acts, mostly attacks on Jewish memorials, synagogues and cemeteries but also a number of physical attacks against Jews.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Most of the antisemitic incidents in Eastern Europe are against Jewish cemeteries and buildings (community centers and synagogues).
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] According to Paul Johnson, antisemitic policies are a sign of a state which is poorly governed.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] While no European state currently has such policies, the Economist Intelligence Unit notes the rise in political uncertainty, notably populism and nationalism, as something that is particularly alarming for Jews.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Robert Bernstein, founder of Human Rights Watch, says that antisemitism is "deeply ingrained and institutionalized" in "Arab nations in modern times".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In a 2011 survey by the Pew Research Center, all of the Muslim-majority Middle Eastern countries polled held significantly negative opinions of Jews.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In the questionnaire, only 2% of Egyptians, 3% of Lebanese Muslims, and 2% of Jordanians reported having a positive view of Jews.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Muslim-majority countries outside the Middle East similarly held markedly negative views of Jews, with 4% of Turks and 9% of Indonesians viewing Jews favorably.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] According to a 2011 exhibition at the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum in Washington, United States, some of the dialogue from Middle East media and commentators about Jews bear a striking resemblance to Nazi propaganda.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] According to Josef Joffe of *Newsweek*, "anti-Semitism—the real stuff, not just bad-mouthing particular Israeli policies—is as much part of Arab life today as the hijab or the hookah.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Muslim clerics in the Middle East have frequently referred to Jews as descendants of apes and pigs, which are conventional epithets for Jews and Christians.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] According to professor Robert Wistrich, director of the Vidal Sassoon International Center for the Study of Antisemitism (SICSA), the calls for the destruction of Israel by Iran or by Hamas, Hezbollah, Islamic Jihad, or the Muslim Brotherhood, represent a contemporary mode of genocidal antisemitism.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] After the 2023 Hamas-led attack on Israel on 7 October and Israel's subsequent invasion of the Gaza strip, antisemitism and anti-Jewish hate crimes around the world increased significantly.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Multiple universities and university officials have been accused of systemic antisemitism.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] On 1 May 2024, the United States House of Representatives voted 320–91 in favour of adopting a bill enshrining the International Holocaust Remembrance Alliance definition of antisemitism into law.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The bill was opposed by some who claimed it conflated criticism of Israel with antisemitism, while Jewish advocacy groups like the American Jewish Committee and World Jewish Congress generally supported it in response to the increase in antisemitic incidents on university campuses.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] An open letter by 1,200 Jewish professors opposed the proposal.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Extremist groups of Black Hebrew Israelites believe that Jewish people are "imposters", who have "stolen" Black Americans' true racial and religious identity.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Some of these groups also promote the unsupported Khazar hypothesis of Ashkenazi ancestry.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In 2022, the American Jewish Committee stated that the Black Hebrew Israelite claim that "we are the real Jews" is a "troubling antisemitic trope with dangerous potential," arguing that such rhetoric perpetuates antisemitism by denying Jewish people's legitimacy as Jews.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The perpetrators of several antisemitic attacks in the United States have expressed interest in the Black Hebrew Israelites.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Between 2019 and 2022, individuals motivated by Black Hebrew Israelites committed five religiously motivated murders.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In September 2022, the Program on Extremism at George Washington University published a report which said the largest threat came from "individuals loosely affiliated with or inspired by the movement", rather than from formal members of Black Hebrew Israelite organizations.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Antisemitism has been explained in terms of racism, xenophobia, projected guilt, displaced aggression, conspiracy theory, and the search for a scapegoat.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] As another example, Walter Laqueur suggested that the antisemitic perception of Jewish people as greedy (as often used in stereotypes of Jews) probably evolved in Europe during medieval times where a large portion of money lending was operated by Jews.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Its foundation lies in the early claim of Jewish deicide and depictions of Jews as 'Christ-killers'.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Throughout Western history, Jews have since been used as a symbolic 'other' to define and articulate the values and boundaries of various cultures and intellectual traditions.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In philosophy, literature, and politics, Jewishness has often been constructed as a counterpoint to what is considered normative or ideal.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] One of the key insights from Nirenberg's work is that antisemitism has proven to be remarkably adaptable.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] It changes form and adapts to different contexts and times, whether in medieval religious disputes, Enlightenment critiques, or modern racial theories.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Philosophers and intellectuals have often used 'Jewishness' as a foil to explore and define their ideas.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] For instance, in the Enlightenment, figures like Voltaire critiqued Judaism as backward and superstitious to promote their visions of reason and progress.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Similarly, the Soviet Union frequently portrayed Judaism as linked with capitalism and mercantilism, standing in opposition to the ideals of proletarian solidarity and communism.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In each case, Judaism or the Jews are portrayed as standing in tension with prevailing moral norms.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In it, Horn argues that antisemitism functions by appropriating what has happened to Jews and recasting their experience as part of a broader, universal struggle, which always ends in ultimately redefining Jewish identity as incompatible with these ideals.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] She concludes that the attacks on Jews, often under the guise of anti-Zionism, follow the same ancient pattern of marginalization and vilification.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Education plays an important role in addressing and overcoming prejudice and countering social discrimination.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Education equips learners with the knowledge to identify antisemitism and biased or prejudiced messages and raises awareness about the forms, manifestations, and impact of antisemitism faced by Jews and Jewish communities.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Some Jewish writers have argued that public education about antisemitism through the prism of the Holocaust is unhelpful at best or actively deepening antisemitism at worst.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Dara Horn wrote in *The Atlantic* that "Auschwitz is not a metaphor", arguing "That the Holocaust drives home the importance of love is an idea, like the idea that Holocaust education prevents anti-Semitism, that seems entirely unobjectionable.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The Holocaust didn't happen because of a lack of love.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Instead, she argues that perhaps "a more effective way to address anti-Semitism might lie in cultivating a completely different quality, one that happens to be the key to education itself: curiosity.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Why use Jews as a means to teach people that we're all the same, when the demand that Jews be just like their neighbors is exactly what embedded the mental virus of anti-Semitism in the Western mind in the first place?
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] State Department found that there was an increase in antisemitism across the world, and that both old and new expressions of antisemitism persist.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights and Labor also noted a continued global increase in antisemitism, and found that Holocaust denial and opposition to Israeli policy at times was used to promote or justify blatant antisemitism.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In August 2024, the Israeli Ministry of Diaspora Affairs announced a new antisemitism monitoring project.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] The goal of the project is to measure levels of antisemitism in various countries, as well as identify instigators and trends.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/antisemitism-p02] In the event that antisemitism in a given country becomes severe, the Diaspora Minister may contact that country's government in an official capacity.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/bananas] The film was criticized by Dole for containing "patent falsehoods".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/bananas] After a screening at the Los Angeles Film Festival in June 2009, Gertten was sued for defamation by Dole on 8 July.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/bananas] The lawsuit was preceded by threats of legal action from Dole aimed against the LA Film Festival, which resulted in sponsors pulling support and the film being removed from competition.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/bananas] Dole dropped their lawsuit against Fredrik Gertten and *Bananas!** on 15 October 2009.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/bananas] In September 2009, the Swedish parliament members Mats Johansson (M) and Luciano Astudillo (S) took the initiative of displaying the movie in the Parliament of Sweden, this being its premiere in Sweden.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/bananas] In late 2010 a court in Los Angeles decided in favor of the movie crew, making it possible to release the film in the US.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/bananas] A judge awarded the filmmakers nearly $200,000 in fees and costs.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/bananas] In 2011, Gertten directed the film *Big Boys Gone Bananas!** about how the company was sued by Dole.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/big-boys-gone-bananas] The film concerns events that began when Dole sent a cease-and-desist letter to the filmmaker, the 2009 Los Angeles Film Festival, and the festival’s sponsors, that alleged that *Bananas!** was false and defamatory, though the film had not yet been screened.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/big-boys-gone-bananas] In June, a scathing review of *Bananas!** appeared on the front page of the *Los Angeles Business Journal*.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/big-boys-gone-bananas] The Los Angeles Film Festival removed the film from the competition and screened it separately as a "case study" rather than a documentary.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/big-boys-gone-bananas] Many critics saw this procedure as undermining the original documentary's claims.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/big-boys-gone-bananas] European channels screened *Big Boys Gone Bananas!** and there was a threatened boycott of Dole fruits in Sweden.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/big-boys-gone-bananas] The film was positively reviewed in major newspapers.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/big-boys-gone-bananas] Most reviewers described how the film demonstrated how easily media companies and journalists, especially in the United States, caved quickly to the threat of negative publicity generated by Dole's lawsuit.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/big-boys-gone-bananas] Numerous critics invoked the phrase "David and Goliath" in reference to the difference between an independent filmmaker and a multinational corporation.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/big-boys-gone-bananas] One critic in the *Los Angeles Times* remarked that the film did not examine allegations of fraud against workers’ attorneys in the first film.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/big-boys-gone-bananas] The review in *The Hollywood Reporter* described the film as "of limited commercial interest, though it raises issues with broad appeal." The film's Skype interviews with Gertten were also critiqued.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] The film focuses on the coffee growers of the Oromia Region of southern and western Ethiopia, the birthplace of coffee.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] He also travels to England and the United States in an effort to promote Ethiopian coffee by eliminating the numerous middlemen.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] There is also a scene where coffee farmers pray to God for a higher price, which was filmed at the Negele Gorbitu Cooperative, located near Irgachefe in the Abaya woreda of the Borena Zone.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] Other footage was shot at the first Starbucks and the World Barista Championship at the 2005 Specialty Coffee Association of America conference in Seattle; and at a café and the Illy coffee company in Trieste, Italy.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] These scenes stand in stark contrast to the footage of the impoverished conditions faced by the Ethiopian coffee farmers and their families.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] In July 2003, Nick Francis and Marc James Francis travelled to Ethiopia and started making the film.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] The meeting with Tadesse Meskela, the manager of Oromia Coffee Farmers Co-operative Union, was a decisive moment in the production of the film.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] The Ethiopian footage was filmed on two occasions (in 2003 and 2005), for six weeks each time.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] Unprecedented, that year developing countries refused to be forced into signing agreements that were against their interests, and the WTO talks completely collapsed.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] After the team's return to the UK, they spent the following months developing a rough cut of *Black Gold*.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] During these months, the direction of the film took shape, along with the rest of the necessary shoots meant to develop the thrust of the narrative.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] In 2005, the team returned to Ethiopia for further shoots.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] Although Starbucks, Sara Lee, Procter & Gamble, Kraft, and Nestlé—the world's largest sellers of coffee—are mentioned in the film, all five companies declined invitations to be interviewed for the film.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] By the end of 2005, the final cut of *Black Gold* was done and officially premiered during the 2006's edition of Sundance Film Festival.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] Andreas Kapsalis, whom Marc James Francis and Nick Francis met during the Sundance Documentary Composers Lab, wrote the final soundtrack.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] In doing so, he used in part Mathew Coldrick's Ethiopian instrumental samples, recorded from Ethiopia.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] Joe Henson, Kunja Chatterton, and Mathew Herbert also contributed to the soundtrack.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] In the first few weeks after the premiere, the film helped to generate donations approximately up to $25,000.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] The dilapidated school featured in the film was built.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] Tadesse Meskela, the main character in *Black Gold*, was able to increase the market price for his cooperative union's coffee.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] Tadesse Meskela was invited to 10 Downing Street, where he took his message directly to Tony Blair.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] After seeing the film, the UN have invited Tadesse to New York to do a presentation about his co-operatives at the 46th Session of the Commission for Social Development.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] Since the first showing of *Black Gold* during Sundance, Starbucks sent people to screenings of the film in what has been called by one journalist "going on a charm offensive".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] As the film became more and more popular, Starbucks flew Tadesse and four other African coffee producers to their Seattle headquarters for a weekend conference, which was seen by many as a PR stunt.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] Further, just before the film premiered at the London Film Festival in October 2006, a memo received by Starbucks staff from the headquarters leaked to the *Black Gold forum*.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/black-gold-2006-film] The internal memo was sent out to inform all Starbucks employees that *Black Gold* was "incomplete and inaccurate".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] A **boycott** is an act of nonviolent, voluntary abstention from a product, person, organization, or country as an expression of protest.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] It is usually for moral, social, political, or environmental reasons.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] The purpose of a boycott is to inflict some economic loss on the target, or to indicate a moral outrage, usually to try to compel the target to alter an objectionable behavior.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] The word is named after Captain Charles Boycott, agent of an absentee landlord in Ireland, against whom the tactic was successfully employed after a suggestion by Irish nationalist leader Charles Stewart Parnell and his Irish Land League in 1880.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Sometimes, a boycott can be a form of consumer activism, sometimes called moral purchasing.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] When a similar practice is legislated by a national government, it is known as a sanction.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Frequently, however, the threat of boycotting a business is an empty threat, with no significant effect on sales.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] The word *boycott* entered the English language during the Irish "Land War" and derives from Captain Charles Boycott, the land agent of an absentee landlord, Lord Erne, who lived in County Mayo, Ireland.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Captain Boycott was the target of social ostracism organized by the Irish Land League in 1880.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] As harvests had been poor that year, Lord Erne offered his tenants a ten percent reduction in their rents.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] In September of that year, protesting tenants demanded a twenty-five percent reduction, which Lord Erne refused.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Boycott then attempted to evict eleven tenants from the land.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Charles Stewart Parnell, an Irish leader, proposed that when dealing with tenants who take farms where another tenant was evicted, rather than resorting to violence, everyone in the locality should shun them.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] While Parnell's speech did not refer to land agents or landlords, the tactic was first applied to Boycott when the alarm was raised about the evictions.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Despite the short-term economic hardship to those undertaking this action, Boycott soon found himself isolated – his workers stopped work in the fields and stables, as well as in his house.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Local businessmen stopped trading with him, and the local postman refused to deliver mail.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] The concerted action taken against him meant that Boycott was unable to hire anyone to harvest his crops in his charge.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] After the harvest, the "boycott" was successfully continued and soon the new word was everywhere.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] A *New-York Tribune* reporter, James Redpath, first wrote of the boycott in the international press.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] The Irish author George Moore reported: 'Like a comet the verb 'boycott' appeared.' It was used by *The Times* in November 1880 as a term for organized isolation.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] According to an account in the book *The Fall of Feudalism in Ireland* by Michael Davitt, the term was promoted by Fr.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] John O'Malley of County Mayo to "signify ostracism applied to a landlord or agent like Boycott".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Although the term itself was not coined until 1880, the practice dates back to at least the 1790s, when supporters of the British abolitionists led and supported the free produce movement.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] During the 1973 oil crisis, the Arab countries enacted a crude oil embargo against the West.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Other examples include the US-led boycott of the 1980 Summer Olympics in Moscow, the Soviet-led boycott of the 1984 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles, and the movement that advocated "disinvestment" in South Africa during the 1980s in opposition to that country's apartheid regime.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] The first Olympic boycott was in the 1956 Summer Olympics with several countries boycotting the games for different reasons.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Iran also has an informal Olympic boycott against participating against Israel, whereby Iranian athletes typically bow out or claim injuries when pitted against Israelis (see Arash Miresmaeili).
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Academic boycotts have been organized against countries—for example, the mid- and late 20th-century academic boycotts of South Africa in protest of apartheid practices and the academic boycotts of Israel in the early 2000s.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] In May 2006, Great American Boycott, also called the Day Without an Immigrant, took place across the United States.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] In studies of political consumerism, boycotts are often distinguished from “buycotts”.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] A boycott involves withholding purchases or support from a target, while a buycott involves deliberately supporting a company, product, or service because of its perceived political, social, or ethical conduct.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Boycotts are now much easier to successfully initiate due to the Internet.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Examples include the gay and lesbian boycott of advertisers of the *Dr.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Laura* talk show, gun owners' similar boycott of advertisers of Rosie O'Donnell's talk show and (later) magazine, and gun owners' boycott of Smith & Wesson following that company's March 2000 settlement with the Clinton administration.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] They may be initiated very easily using either websites (the *Dr.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Laura* boycott), newsgroups (the Rosie O'Donnell boycotts), or even mailing lists.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Internet-initiated boycotts "snowball" very quickly compared to other forms of organization.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Some boycotts center on particular businesses, such as recent protests regarding Costco, Walmart, Ford Motor Company, or the diverse products of Philip Morris.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Another form of boycott identifies a number of different companies involved in a particular issue, such as the Sudan Divestment campaign, the "Boycott Bush" campaign.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] The Boycott Bush website was set up by Ethical Consumer after U.S.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Bush failed to ratify the Kyoto Protocol – the website identified Bush's corporate funders and the brands and products they produce.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Historically boycotts have also targeted individual businesses.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] During the early decades of the twentieth century, hotels in Australia were regularly targeted over the cost of alcohol, accommodation and food, as well as mistreatment of employees.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Pope Francis refers to boycotting as a successful means of influencing businesses, "forcing them to consider their environmental footprint and their patterns of production".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Mobile applications have also been developed to support consumer boycotts by allowing users to scan barcodes or search brand names against campaign-specific boycott lists.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Coverage of some such apps has raised questions about the reliability of the sources and criteria used to classify companies or products.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] As a response to consumer boycotts of large-scale and multinational businesses, some companies have marketed brands that do not bear the company's name on the packaging or in advertising.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Activists such as Ethical Consumer produce information that reveals which companies own which brands and products so consumers can practice boycotts or moral purchasing more effectively.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Another organization, Buycott.com, provides an Internet-based smart-phone application that scans Universal Product Codes and displays corporate relationships to the user.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] "Boycotts" may be formally organized by governments as well.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] In reality, government "boycotts" are just a type of embargo.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Notably, the first formal, nationwide act of the Nazi government against German Jews was a national embargo of Jewish businesses on April 1, 1933.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Where the target of a boycott derives all or part of its revenues from other businesses, as a newspaper does, boycott organizers may address the target's commercial customers.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] The sociology of collective behavior is concerned with causes and conditions pertaining to behavior carried out by a collective, as opposed to an individual (e.g., riots, panics, fads/crazes, boycotts).
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Boycotts have been characterized by some as different from traditional forms of collective behavior in that they appear to be highly rational and dependent on existing norms and structures.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Lewis Killian criticizes that characterization, pointing to the Tallahassee bus boycott as one example of a boycott that aligns with traditional collective behavior theory.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Philip Balsiger points out that political consumption (e.g., boycotts) tends to follow dual-purpose action repertoires, or scripts, which are used publicly to pressure boycott targets and to educate and recruit consumers.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Balsiger finds one example in Switzerland, documenting activities of the Clean Clothes Campaign, a public NGO-backed campaign, that highlighted and disseminated information about local companies' ethical practices.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Dixon, Martin, and Nau analyzed 31 collective behavior campaigns against corporations that took place during the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Protests considered successful included boycotts and were found to include a third party, either in the capacity of state intervention or of media coverage.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] State intervention may make boycotts more efficacious when corporation leaders fear the imposition of regulations.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Media intervention may be a crucial contributor to a successful boycott because of its potential to damage the reputation of a corporation.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Target corporations that were the most visible were found to be the most vulnerable to either market (protest causing economic loss) or mediated (caused by third-party) disruption.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] The boycott, a prima facie market-disruptive tactic, often precipitates mediated disruption.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] The researchers' analysis led them to conclude that when boycott targets are highly visible and directly interact with and depend on local consumers who can easily find substitutes, they are more likely to make concessions.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Koku, Akhigbe, and Springer also emphasize the importance of boycotts' threat of reputational damage, finding that boycotts alone pose more of a threat to a corporation's reputation than to its finances directly.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Philippe Delacote points out that a problem contributing to a generally low probability of success for any boycott is the fact that the consumers with the most power to cause market disruption are the least likely to participate; the opposite is true for consumers with the least power.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Another collective behavior problem is the difficulty, or impossibility, of direct coordination amongst a dispersed group of boycotters.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Yuksel and Mryteza emphasize the collective behavior problem of free riding in consumer boycotts, noting that some individuals may perceive participating to be too great an immediate personal utility sacrifice.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] They also note that boycotting consumers took the collectivity into account when deciding to participate, that is, consideration of joining a boycott as goal-oriented collective activity increased one's likelihood of participating.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Boycotts are generally legal in developed countries.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] When the boycott first emerged in Ireland, it presented a serious dilemma for William Ewart Gladstone's government.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] The individual actions that constituted a boycott were recognized by legislators as essential to a free society.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] However, overall a boycott amounted to a harsh, extrajudicial punishment.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] The Prevention of Crime (Ireland) Act 1882 made it illegal to use "intimidation" to instigate or enforce a boycott, but not to participate in one.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] The 19th-century conservative jurist James Fitzjames Stephen justified laws against boycotting by claiming that the practice amounted to "usurpation of the functions of government" and ought therefore to be dealt with as "the modern representatives of the old conception of high treason".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] The right to engage in commerce, social intercourse, and friendship includes the implied right not to engage in commerce, social intercourse, and friendship.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Since a boycott is voluntary and nonviolent, the law cannot stop it.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Opponents of boycotts historically have the choice of suffering under it, yielding to its demands, or attempting to suppress it through extralegal means, such as force and coercion.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] In the United States, the antiboycott provisions of the Export Administration Regulations (EAR) apply to all "U.S. persons", defined to include individuals and companies located in the United States and their foreign affiliates.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] The antiboycott provisions are intended to prevent United States citizens and companies being used as instrumentalities of a foreign government's foreign policy.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] The EAR forbids participation in or material support of boycotts initiated by foreign governments; for example, the Arab League boycott of Israel.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] These persons are subject to the law when their activities relate to the sale, purchase, or transfer of goods or services (including the sale of information) within the United States or between the United States and a foreign country.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] This covers exports and imports, financing, forwarding and shipping, and certain other transactions that may take place wholly offshore.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Other legal impediments to certain boycotts remain.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] One set are refusal to deal laws, which prohibit concerted efforts to eliminate competition by refusal to buy from or to sell to a party.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] A boycott is typically a one-time affair intended to correct an outstanding single wrong.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] When extended for a long period of time, or as part of an overall program of awareness-raising or reforms to laws or regimes, a boycott is part of moral purchasing, and some prefer those economic or political terms.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Another form of consumer boycotting is substitution for an equivalent product; for example, Mecca Cola and Qibla Cola have been marketed as substitutes for Coca-Cola among Muslim populations.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] A prime target of boycotts is consumerism itself, e.g.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] "International Buy Nothing Day" celebrated globally on the Friday after Thanksgiving Day in the United States.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Another version of the boycott is targeted divestment, or disinvestment.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Targeted divestment involves campaigning for withdrawal of investment; for example, the Sudan Divestment campaign involves putting pressure on companies, often through shareholder activism, to withdraw investment that helps the Sudanese government perpetuate genocide in Darfur.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Only if a company refuses to change its behavior in response to shareholder engagement does the targeted divestment model call for divestment from that company.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Such targeted divestment implicitly excludes companies involved in agriculture, the production and distribution of consumer goods, or the provision of goods and services intended to relieve human suffering or to promote health, religious and spiritual activities, or education.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] The 1936 Summer Olympics in Berlin were held after the Nazis rose to power three years prior.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Despite advocacy from numerous officials and activists, no country boycotted the games, although the United States was close to it.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] In the 1970s and 1980s South Africa became the target of a sports boycott.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] After the Soviet Union invaded Afghanistan in 1979, the United States led a 66-nation boycott of the 1980 Moscow Olympics much to Soviet chagrin.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] The USSR then organized an Eastern Bloc boycott of the 1984 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles, which allowed the Americans to win far more medals than expected.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Viewership of the game dropped in the city by half compared to Super Bowl LII, contributing to a noticeable drop in the overall national ratings, but the boycott failed to achieve any meaningful remedy for the Saints or their fans.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] Nations have from time to time used "diplomatic boycotts" to isolate other governments.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] A diplomatic boycott is when diplomatic participation is withheld from an event such as the Olympics but athletic participation is not limited.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/boycott] In 2021, a number of Western nations, led by the United States, Britain and Canada, protested the 2022 Beijing Winter Olympics through a diplomatic boycott, citing China's policies concerning the persecution of Uyghurs and human rights violations in the country.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] A **cease and desist** letter is a document sent by one party, often a business, to warn another party that they believe the other party is committing an unlawful act, such as copyright infringement, and that they will take legal action if the other party continues the alleged unlawful activity.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] The letter may warn that, if the recipient does not discontinue specified conduct, or take certain actions, by deadlines set in the letter, the letter's recipient may be sued.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] The phrase "cease and desist" is a legal doublet, made up of two near-synonyms.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] A cease and desist letter issued by a government entity, called a **cease and desist order**, is "a warning of impending judicial enforcement".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] The holder of an intellectual property right such as a copyrighted work, a trademark, or a patent, may send the cease and desist letter to inform a third party "of the right holder's rights, identity, and intentions to enforce the rights".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] The letter may merely contain a licensing offer or may be an explicit threat of a lawsuit.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] A cease and desist letter often triggers licensing negotiations, and is a frequent first step towards litigation.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] Receiving numerous cease and desist letters may be very costly for the recipient.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] Cease and desist letters are sometimes used to intimidate recipients and can be "an effective tool used by corporations to chill the critical speech of gripe sites operators".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] To prevent genericizing and potential loss of its trademark, Google has discouraged use of the word *google* as a verb, particularly when used as a synonym for general web searching.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] On February 23, 2003, Google sent a cease and desist letter to Paul McFedries, creator of Word Spy, a website that tracks neologisms.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] In an article in *The Washington Post*, Frank Ahrens discussed the letter he received from a Google lawyer that demonstrated "appropriate" and "inappropriate" ways to use the verb *google*.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] Author Patrick Wensink used Jack Daniel's famous branding without licensing as a cover for his 2012 book *Broken Piano for President*.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] Jack Daniel's requested only future printings of the book to have the cover changed and offered compensation.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] In September 2012, AwardWallet, TripIt and MileWise received a number of cease and desist letters from American Airlines, Delta, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines, demanding that companies discontinue accessing their websites for tracking clients' miles rewards programs.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] In 2017, a cease and desist letter sent by Netflix for an unauthorized *Stranger Things*–related bar event was noted by news outlets such as *Fortune* and *Quartz* for its humorous wording.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] Donald Trump sent a cease and desist letter to CNN asking them to retract a poll that showed him being 14 percentage points behind his opponent Joe Biden during the 2020 U.S. presidential election, prompting *The Atlantic* to warn about attacks on the media.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] In 2021, Google's platform YouTube issued a significant number of cease and desist notices to the creators of various music bots on Discord, such as Rythm and Groovy.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] These music bots allowed users to request songs and have the bot create a queue.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] This was done by pulling the audio stream from various streaming and video platforms, including YouTube, and then played that audio on the Discord voice channel.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] Because such music bots did not play any of the advertisements included on the video-hosting site, the company alleged missing revenue for itself and the content uploaders.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] A spokesperson for Google told *The Verge* that Groovy violated YouTube's terms of service for "modifying the service and using it for commercial purposes".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] The makers of Groovy had decided to comply with Google's request by shutting down the bot on August 30, 2021.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] According to estimations, the bot had more than 250 million users.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] In 2022, Disney issued a letter of cease and desist to the creators of *Club Penguin Rewritten*, a game that was created as a remake of *Club Penguin* after its shutdown on March 31, 2017.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] Google issued a letter of cease and desist to the creators of YouTube Vanced, an Android app developed as a third-party modification of YouTube.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] The app, which utilizes the apk file format, allowed its users to skip advertisements, among other functions.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] Since March 13, 2022, the app has been discontinued, with all links being removed.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] Nintendo issued a letter of cease and desist to the creators of Yuzu, a video game console emulator for the Nintendo Switch.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] The program allowed its users to not pay or participate in grinding for downloadable content, such as all of its Booster Course Passes and a Gold Mario for *Mario Kart 8*.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] In August 2025, the Roblox Corporation sent a YouTuber known as "Schlep" a cease-and-desist letter for catching child predators.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] Roblox also terminated all of his accounts.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] The Philippine National Telecommunications Commission administered a cease and desist order against ABS-CBN to stop broadcasting on May 5, 2020, after its franchise expired the day before (May 4, 2020).
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] At 7:52 pm (PHT), ABS-CBN stopped its broadcast in compliance with the NTC's letter, signing off all of its free TV and radio stations across the country (ABS-CBN Channel 2, S+A Channel 23, DZMM 630, and MOR 101.9).
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] The said agency also gave ABS-CBN ten days to explain why its assigned frequencies should not be recalled.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] On June 30, 2020, considering that Channel 43 was also included in the May 5, 2020 shutdown order issued by the NTC against ABS-CBN (although ABS-CBN CEO Carlo L.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/cease-and-desist] On January 22, 2024, the National Telecommunications Commission issued a cease-and-desist order to Sonshine Media Network International, citing its failure to comply with the original 30-day suspension order issued by the said agency.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] The book is divided into two sections: "The American Way" and "Meat and Potatoes".
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] "The American Way" the first part, takes a historical view of the fast food business by analyzing its beginnings within post-World War II America while "Meat and Potatoes" examines the specific mechanisms of the fast-food industry within a modern context as well as its influence.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] The first section of *Fast Food Nation* opens with a discussion of Carl N.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] Karcher and the McDonald brothers, examining their roles as pioneers of the fast-food industry in southern California.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] This discussion is followed by an examination of Ray Kroc and Walt Disney's complicated relationship before ending with the consideration of the intricate, profitable methods of advertising to children.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] Next, Schlosser visits Colorado Springs, CO and investigates the life and working conditions of the typical fast-food industry employee, learning how fast-food restaurants pay minimum wage to a higher proportion of their employees than any other American industry.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] The second section of the text begins with a discussion of the chemical components that make the food taste so good.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] Schlosser follows this with a discussion of the life of a typical rancher, considering the difficulties presented to the agricultural world in a new economy.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] Schlosser analyzes the meatpacking industry, which he tags as the most dangerous job in America.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] Moreover, the meat produced by slaughterhouses has become increasingly hazardous since the centralization of the industry due to the way cattle are raised, slaughtered, and processed, providing an ideal setting for E coli to spread.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] Additionally, working conditions continue to grow worse.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] In the final chapter, Schlosser considers how fast food has matured as an American cultural export following the Cold War and how the collapse of Soviet Communism allowed the mass spread of American goods and services, especially fast food.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] As a result, the rest of the world is catching up with America's rising obesity rates.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] In the 2012 edition, Schlosser published a revised edition that included an afterword.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] In the afterword, he looks back at the relevance and criticism of the first edition and how it inspired other works as well as how the fast food industry has evolved in the ten years following the book, including its effects on policy and childhood obesity rates.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] He concluded that, given the swift, decisive and effective action that took place as a result of this interest and intervention, many of the problems documented in the book are solvable, given enough political will.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] The afterword can also be read in an article penned by Schlosser at *The Daily Beast*.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] For example, Schlosser suggests that hundreds have died from E. coli infections as a result of eating fast food.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] However, as Walker points out, "[Schlosser] extrapolated his figures from an annual total in a report on food-related illness, which itself relied on a good deal of extrapolation.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] Julia Livshin, writing for *The Atlantic*, believes "Schlosser's book is not just a compendium of kitchen horror stories.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] The book won the 2002 Firecracker Alternative Book Award for Nonfiction.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] Terrie Dort, president of the National Council of Chain Restaurants, the trade association representing many of the country's major fast-food chains, released this statement about Schlosser and his book: "It is unfortunate that Mr.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] Schlosser's book, 'Fast Food Nation,' categorizes the entire fast-food industry in such a negative light.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] The restaurant companies that comprise the industry provide employment to hundreds of thousands of workers across the country and offer consumers a wide variety in menu options and prices.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] An adaptation of *Fast Food Nation* for younger readers titled *Chew on This: Everything You Don't Want to Know about Fast Food* was published in May 2006 by Houghton Mifflin.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] *Chew on This* was first published in 2006, is an adaptation of the main work created by Schlosser and Charles Wilson for younger readers.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] This book follows the general plot structure of *Fast Food Nation*, but simplifies its predecessor's original content to make it more readable for younger children.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] Some critical reception has been positive.
[src:big-boys-gone-bananas/chew-on-this] Common Sense Media gave the book 4/5 stars, but writing that "...the photographs seem randomly placed throughout the book, and the narrative can wander a bit.
